\f0\fs28 \cf2 In March 2018, the Guardian broke the story that a data analytics firm, hired by Donald Trump\'92s 2016  election team, had harvested data from the facebook profiles of millions of US voters.\
\
Cambridge Analytica, used personal information (collected without authorisation) to create a process whereby US voters could be profiled and targeted with specific political advertising. \
\
This data breach, of one of the world\'92s largest companies, cast not only doubt on Trump\'92s 2016 election win but other political campaigns that worked with Cambridge Analytica, including the Leave campaign during the Brexit referendum and many other campaigns across the globe.\
\
The scandal revealed not only how our personal data can be used and manipulated for advertising and political gain but also brought into question the idea of data privacy and consent.\cf0 \
\
\
\
\
\cf3 In 2014, Cambridge Analytica formed relationships with US billionaire Robert Mercer and would be CEO of Trump\'92s presidential bid,  Steve Bannon. \cf0 \
\
\cf4 Not long after this a Cambridge professor, Alexander Kogan, approached the firm with the idea of harvesting voter data through a series of his apps on Facebook.\cf0 \
\
\cf4 These apps held special permissions from Facebook in collecting not only consenting users\'92 information but also their non-consenting friend\'92s network.\
\cf0 \
\cf5 They would only need thousands to sign up to these apps to infiltrate and gather the data of millions - the firm acquired the data from Kogan.\cf0 \
\
\cf6 Despite learning of this and only getting thin assurance from both Kogan and Cambridge Analytica that the data would be deleted, Facebook failed to properly follow up which allowed Trump\'92s campaign team to exploit US voters through a series of targeted ad campaigns\cf0 . \
\
\cf4 Since the scandal was revealed in 2018, Cambridge Analytica has ceased to exist, Mark Zuckerberg has been summoned to appear in both the US senate and EU parliament and Facebook has suffered a dip in usage,\
\cf0 \
\cf3 but the questions of data privacy and consent remain.\
\cf0 \
