\cf2 The challenges and ambiguities \cf0 \
\
\
\cf3 In the modern world, the rise of social media has seen millions upon millions sign up to different  platforms and willingly give over personal information. \
\cf0 \
\cf5 People value their private lives so much they publish it to a public platform and yet in doing so are also neglectful of their own privacy\cf0 \
\
\cf3  this is the idea of Neo-privacy - coined by Prof. William Watkin\
\cf0 \
\
\cf4 \
Users are essentially selling their personal data to an open market, giving permission for it to be monetised by social media companies.\
\
How can we cry fowl when we give our private data away so easily?\cf0 \
\
\cf6 Cambridge analytics and Kogan tapped into the idea of Neo-privacy and built a model that exploited both Facebook and its users.\
\
This opens up a ethical debate\
\
It can be said that when Kogan sold his data to Cambridge Analytica he broke the law as it violated the terms of the Facebook API.\
\
But only 2 years previously, before FB changed their API, President Obama team\'92s used a similar approach in gathering data on voters.\
\
How can we stop this from happening again?\cf0 \
\
\
